caption: This is an impressive church currently under renovations (as indicated on the huge billboard hung outside), but you can get inside and enjoy its beautiful architecture as well as it stained glass windows. If you pass by La Gare Saint Lazare, it's only a few minutes walk from there, try not to miss it. Just look at the attached pictures.
A very pleasing cathedral.  A lot of renovation was going on so we didn't get to enjoy all it's beauty.
Although it is going thru renovations, it was beautiful from the street. Has a nice little garden in front. Surrounded by neighborhoods, restaurants, shops, and train stations. Lovely area.
I was sorry to see that the entrance was still under reconstruction but glad to see that the church was open. It is a nice 19th century big-hall church.
They are at the refurbishment stage. There was an adoration while we get there

The √âglise de la Sainte-Trinit√© is a Roman Catholic church located in the 9th arrondissement of Paris. The church is a building of the Second Empire period, built between 1861 and 1867 at a cost of almost 5 million francs.  La Trinit√©, as it is known, was designed by Th√©odore Ballu as part of the beautification and reorganization of Paris under Baron Haussmann. Exterior figures of Faith, Hope, and Charity on the church were sculpted by Eug√®ne-Louis Lequesne. The 93 meter-long church has a bell tower 63 metres high topped by a dome. The choir is ten steps higher than the nave and surrounded by an ambulatory.[1] Also named after it are the rue de La Trinit√© and the square de La Trinit√©.  The church is accessible by the M√©tro (the nearby station, Trinit√©, is named after it) and is known internationally for its former organist, the French composer Olivier Messiaen. It was the location of Gioachino Rossini's funeral, on 13 November 1868, Hector Berlioz's funeral, on 11 March 1869, and Georges Bizet's funeral in 1875.  The church's facade served as the inspiration for the design of the Saint-Jean-Baptiste Church in Quebec City[2] and the Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament in Sacramento, California.
Young crowd for the Sunday evening mass.
Scaffolding hides it. Inside a mess is going on as I try to visit.

Currently having some works done to the front of the building so you can only enter through a side door with a ramp and steps they have built to enable access. Little way out of the way of other things but a nice building in itself.

Lovely church to visit - we came specifically to spend time in adoration before the Blessed Sacrament while waiting for our train from Gare St Lazare. It was a short and very easy walk from the train station. The adoration chapel is to the left of the Church once you enter.
One of my favourite churches in Paris except for the huge billboard plastered outside. Such a beautiful interior. Very rare to find a statue of Saint Jude but there is one here.
I visited churches in England, Greece and the States.. this is hands down one of the most intricate and beautiful places of worship I've ever seen!
Packed. Very impressive. Full of young people. very active

Nice architecture, free admission.
Not the most famous church in Paris but one of my favorite. It is big, very well decorated. I visited it last summer during the heatwave, it was so relaxing to get inside.
The church of Saint-Roch Church was built around 1600 . This is a beautiful old baroque church located along in St Honore in Paris. It has a beautiful altar and a distinctive style.

Stunning parish church with neo-baroque interior and eclectic spire, famed as the workplace of composer and organist Olivier Messiaen. Free to enter, but a donation will be gratefully received, particularly given the delapidation of the forecourt garden and steps.
Wonderful Church showing the wonders of French architecture.
Stunning Holly Mass on Sunday evening (7 p.m.) Half hour before (6:30 p.m.) prayers with youngs (Communite Emmanuel) From 5 p.m. quiet time in front of Eucharistic Christ

Amazing gothic looking church which only highlights the amazing artistic work put into the Persian buildings Sadly it was under renovation work when we visited it on our last trip but what we could see left in us awe ...

Small church tucked away in the streets of Paris.

I didn't have the time to go inside the church. But i hope next time i will. It looks a beautiful church.
